g 1425","1320":"1320","1342":"1342","ABT 1390":"omkring 1390","of, Merthyr Tudful, Glamorganshire, Wales":"Merthyr Tydfil, Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom","Wales":"Wales","Kent, England":"Kent, England","Glamorgan, Wales":"Glamorgan, Wales"},"nl":{"1355–1433":"1355–1433","1340–Male":"1340–Overleden","1342–1442":"1342–1442","1355–1445":"1355–1445","1375–1465":"1375–1465","1390–Female":"1390–Overleden","1320–1420":"1320–1420","1300–1425":"1300–1425","1340":"1340","1382":"1382","1390":"1390","1425":"1425","1445":"1445","1433":"1433","1355":"1355","Abt 1420":"circa 1420","1300":"1300","1465":"1465","1420":"1420","1442":"1442","1375":"1375","about 1425":"circa 1425","1320":"1320","1342":"1342","ABT 1390":"circa 1390","of, Merthyr Tudful, Glamorganshire, Wales":"Merthyr Tydfil, Glamorgan, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Wales":"Wales","Kent, England":"Kent, England","Glamorgan, Wales":"Glamorgan, Wales"},"en":{"1355–1433":"1355–1433","1340–Male":"1340–Deceased","1342–1442":"1342–1442","1355–1445":"1355–1445","1375–1465":"1375–1465","1390–Female":"1390–Deceased","1320–1420":"1320–1420","1300–1425":"1300–1425","1340":"1340","1382":"1382","1390":"1390","1425":"1425","1445":"1445","1433":"1433","1355":"1355","Abt 1420":"about 1420","1300":"1300","1465":"1465","1420":"1420","1442":"1442","1375":"1375","about 1425":"about 1425","1320":"1320","1342":"1342","ABT 1390":"about 1390","of, Merthyr Tudful, Glamorganshire, Wales":"Merthyr Tydfil, Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom","Wales":"Wales","Kent, England":"Kent, England","Glamorgan, Wales":"Glamorgan, Wales","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Pye","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (north-West Midlands, Lancashire, Yorkshire, and Norfolk): nickname from Middle English (Old French) <i>pie</i> ‘magpie’, which could be given to someone who wore black and white clothing, had grey-streaked dark hair, or had a loud, chattering voice and impertinent behaviour, or was cunning or sly. The uncomplimentary senses derive from the bird's behavior and are recorded uses of the word in Middle English and early Modern English.","English: occasionally perhaps a topographic or habitational name referring to a house or inn named <i>Pie</i> ‘magpie’. There were two London taverns so named, but whether these gave rise to a hereditary surname is not known. Surnames derived from house and inn signs are rare in English.","English (of Norman origin): nickname from Anglo-Norman French and Middle English <i>pie</i> ‘merciful, compassionate, kind’, a variant of Old French, Anglo-Norman French <i>piu</i>, <i>peu</i>; see   Pew   (2)."],"variants":[{"name":"Pew","meanings":["Welsh: variant of   Pugh  .","English: nickname from Anglo-Norman French <i>pi(u)</i>, <i>piw</i>, <i>peu</i> ‘holy, pious’, also ‘merciful, kind, compassionate’."]},{"name":"Pyatt","meanings":["English (mainly Staffordshire): nickname either from Middle English <i>piot</i> ‘magpie’ (Old French <i>pïot</i>, a diminutive of Old French <i>pie</i>), commonly used to denote a chattering woman, or alternatively from an unrecorded Middle English <i>pyard</i>, an uncomplimentary term derived from the same Old French word + <i>-(h)ard</i>. Compare   Pye  .","Variant of   Piatt  , a surname of French and Walloon origin.","History: This surname (see 2 above) is listed along with the variant <i>Piatt</i> in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors."]},{"name":"Pie","meanings":["English: variant of   Pye  , in part a cognate of 2 below.","French: nickname from Old French <i>pie</i> ‘magpie’, perhaps given to a talkative person or someone who had a loud, chattering voice.","French (<b>Pié</b>): variant of   Piet   ‘foot’. Compare   Pease   and   Pee  ."]}]},{"name":"Walter","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, superseding the native Old English form, <i>Wealdhere</i>. It was a very popular name in medieval England, normally pronounced ‘Water’."],"variants":[{"name":"Walther","meanings":["from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i> ‘army’; name of the famous medieval minnesinger  Walther von der Vogelweide  (  <i>c.</i>1170– <i>c.</i>1230 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":27,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Walter Pye I was born in 1355, in Wales, his father, John ap Ieaun of Merthyr, was 35 and his mother, Jonet ferch Owain, was 55. He had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Elizabeth De La Bere. He died in 1433, in Kent, England, at the age of 78."},"et":{"1355–1433":"1355–1433","1340–Male":"1340–Surnud","1342–1442":"1342–1442","1355–1445":"1355–1445","1375–1465":"1375–1465","1390–Female":"1390–Surnud","1320–1420":"1320–1420","1300–1425":"1300–1425","1340":"1340","1382":"1382","1390":"1390","1425":"1425","1445":"1445","1433":"1433","1355":"1355","Abt 1420":"umbes 1420","1300":"1300","1465":"1465","1420":"1420","1442":"1442","1375":"1375","about 1425":"umbes 1425","1320":"1320","1342":"1342","ABT 1390":"umbes 1390","of, Merthyr Tudful, Glamorganshire, Wales":"Merthyr Tydfil, Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom","Wales":"Wales","Kent, England":"Kent, England","Glamorgan, Wales":"Glamorgan, Wales"},"fi":{"1355–1433":"1355–1433","1340–Male":"1340–Kuollut","1342–1442":"1342–1442","1355–1445":"1355–1445","1375–1465":"1375–1465","1